### Module Details (A‑La‑Carte)

---

#### MODULE 01: ST‑T1024 Core Architecture

**For:** All Engineers  
**Duration:** 2 Weeks  
**Prerequisites:** Embedded systems basics, C/Python

| **Day** | **Topic** | **Practical** |
|---|---|---|
| 1-2 | Introduction to ST‑T1024 — the 7 pillars | Read the standard, understand the vision |
| 3-4 | Tile architecture — FIS, FSM, Ternary Engine | Run `st_t1024_emulator.py` |
| 5-6 | ROM (75%) vs. SRAM (25%) — what goes where | Map a simple application to ROM/SRAM |
| 7-8 | Power gating and AET (680 ns, 3.7 µJ) | Measure AET in emulator |
| 9-10 | Hands‑on: Deploy a simple tile | Deploy a "temperature monitor" tile |

**Deliverable:** A working ST‑T1024 tile (emulated)

---

#### MODULE 02: Ternary Logic & Quantization

**For:** Embedded Systems Engineers, FPGA Engineers  
**Duration:** 2 Weeks  
**Prerequisites:** Digital logic, C, basic arithmetic

| **Day** | **Topic** | **Practical** |
|---|---|---|
| 1-2 | 1.58‑bit ternary logic — why -1, 0, +1 | Implement ternary addition in C |
| 3-4 | XNOR‑based attention — multiplier‑free | Implement XNOR attention |
| 5-6 | Quantization — from floating‑point to ternary | Quantize a simple NN to ternary |
| 7-8 | Precision vs. accuracy — trade‑offs | Benchmark ternary vs. floating‑point |
| 9-10 | Hands‑on: Ternary engine in RISC‑V | Implement ternary operations on RISC‑V |

**Deliverable:** A ternary quantized inference engine

---

#### MODULE 03: FIS Rule Engineering

**For:** Automation Engineers, Control Engineers, Knowledge Engineers  
**Duration:** 3 Weeks  
**Prerequisites:** Control theory, fuzzy logic basics

| **Day** | **Topic** | **Practical** |
|---|---|---|
| 1-2 | Fuzzy Inference Systems — introduction | Understand FIS structure |
| 3-4 | Membership functions and rule bases | Build a simple FIS (temperature control) |
| 5-7 | Rule extraction from experts | Interview a domain expert, extract rules |
| 8-10 | FIS vs. Neural Networks — when to use which | Compare FIS and NN on same problem |
| 11-13 | FIS in ST‑T1024 — integration with tiles | Implement FIS in ST‑T1024 tile |
| 14-15 | Validation and tuning | Test FIS with real sensor data |

**Deliverable:** A validated FIS rule set for an industrial application

---

#### MODULE 04: Tile Design & ROM/SRAM Mapping

**For:** All Engineers  
**Duration:** 3 Weeks  
**Prerequisites:** Module 01

| **Day** | **Topic** | **Practical** |
|---|---|---|
| 1-2 | Domain decomposition — what is a tile? | Decompose a system into tiles |
| 3-4 | ROM content — immutable knowledge (standards, constants) | Populate ROM from NIST, IEC, etc. |
| 5-7 | SRAM content — updatable rules, thresholds, keys | Populate SRAM from factory data |
| 8-10 | Inter‑tile communication and isolation | Design tile handshake protocol |
| 11-13 | Tile evolution — 3‑year cycle | Plan for unsupervised reclustering |
| 14-15 | Hands‑on: Design a multi‑tile system | Boiler example (7 tiles) |

**Deliverable:** A multi‑tile architecture for a real system

---

#### MODULE 05: AET & Certification (IEC 61508, ISO 26262)

**For:** Safety Engineers, Certification Engineers  
**Duration:** 3 Weeks  
**Prerequisites:** Module 01, knowledge of safety standards

| **Day** | **Topic** | **Practical** |
|---|---|---|
| 1-2 | WCET vs. AET — the paradigm shift | Understand the difference |
| 3-4 | AET guarantee — how ST‑T1024 achieves it | Measure AET in emulator |
| 5-7 | IEC 61508 — functional safety, SIL levels | Map ST‑T1024 to IEC 61508 |
| 8-10 | FMEDA — failure modes and diagnostic coverage | Perform FMEDA on a tile |
| 11-13 | Safety manual — how to write it | Draft a safety manual for a boiler tile |
| 14-15 | Certification process — engaging with bodies | Prepare for TÜV, UL assessment |

**Deliverable:** A draft safety case for SIL 2/3

---

#### MODULE 06: Sensor Integration & Deployment

**For:** All Engineers  
